        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Founding AMGEN</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          AMGEN, the biotech giant worth billions today, began humbly with a team of fewer than three people and a shoestring budget of $100,000. <strong>The story starts with William K. Bowes Jr., who developed a keen interest in emerging technologies</strong> after 25 years as an investment banker. His next big bet was AMGEN. Having previously <a href="https://www.amgen.com/stories/2016/12/remembering-bill-bowes---visionary-investor-and-philanthropist" target="_blank">served</a> on the board of Cetus, arguably the first biotechnology company, Bowes recognized the untapped potential of the burgeoning biotech field.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-feb-1-1.png" alt="Founding AMGEN" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          In 1980, Bowes, along with Winston Salser, gathered a small group of scientists and investors at Caltech to discuss an ambitious new venture. <strong>This biotechnology company, focused on recombinant DNA</strong>, had no CEO, product, or marketing plan. What it did have was a little more than a scientific advisory board and a commitment to revolutionize medicine by merging science and business.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Recognizing the need for strong leadership, Bowes made his next critical move: persuading <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-02-2025-george-rathmann" target="_blank">George Rathmann</a>, then Vice President of R&D at Abbott Laboratories, to become Amgen’s first CEO. Known as "Mr. Biotech," Rathmann combined scientific expertise with exceptional business acumen. In 1983, his efforts, alongside CFO Gordon Binder, who joined the same year after his wife suggested AMGEN "will turn into something really big," led to their IPO, raising nearly $40 million.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

 
