          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Cloning success</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          AMGEN was officially incorporated in 1980 in Thousand Oaks, California. The location offered proximity to UCLA and other academic hubs, providing access to both researchers and young graduates seeking employment. The fledgling company operated in a shared industrial space alongside an evangelical choir and a Rolls-Royce warehouse. Resources were limited; scientists worked on cramped lab benches, and the CEO's office was housed in a trailer.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">AMGEN explored a variety of <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-02-2025-ambitious-project" target="_blank">ambitious projects</a>, from cloning firefly proteins to developing organisms capable of extracting oil from shale. While innovative, these early efforts didn’t yield significant breakthroughs.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The turning point came in 1983. That year, the company went public and achieved its first major scientific milestone. <strong>Fu-Kuen Lin, a researcher from Taiwan, successfully cloned the erythropoietin (EPO) gene</strong>, a breakthrough treatment for anemia associated with kidney dialysis. Lin’s work was complemented by University of Chicago professor Eugene Goldwasser, who provided AMGEN with a purified protein containing the genetic code necessary to produce EPO. Interestingly, <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-02-2025-3-goldwasser-chose-amgen" target="_blank">Goldwasser chose AMGEN</a> over its competitor Biogen after being offended when Biogen’s CEO declined to pay for dinner during negotiations.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Epogen, the result of this collaboration, became the <strong>first biologically engineered blockbuster drug</strong>. When Epogen finally hit the market in 1989, it propelled AMGEN’s revenues from $2.8 million in 1989 to $140 million, earning Fortune Magazine’s "Product of the Year" title.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Patent patterns</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Despite the breakthrough in 1983, it took years for Epogen to gain FDA approval. <strong>During its first five years, AMGEN recorded losses and only achieved modest profits by 1986</strong>. Rathmann and Binder navigated these lean times by securing strategic partnerships with Johnson & Johnson, Japan’s Kirin Brewery, and research grants from larger pharmaceutical companies.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-feb-1-2.png" alt="Patent patterns" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">A key factor in AMGEN’s long-term success was its aggressive <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-02-2024-4-patent-strategy" target="_blank">patent strategy</a>. <strong>AMGEN pioneered the concept of a "patent thicket."</strong> It is a network of overlapping intellectual property protections that extended the monopolies on the drugs well beyond the standard 20-year term. While this approach was controversial, it effectively maintained AMGEN’s market dominance.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The profits generated by blockbuster drugs like Epogen, Neupogen, and later Enbrel funded further innovation. <strong>Together, Epogen and Neupogen grossed over $70 billion</strong>, reinforcing AMGEN’s status as a biotech leader and enabling the development of new medicines.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">AMGEN, now worth nearly $150 billion, operates in 100 countries with major facilities in Puerto Rico, Ireland, and the Netherlands. Its Puerto Rico hub, the "City of Amgen," features cutting-edge plants and a DNA helix plaza, symbolizing its commitment to innovation.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
